The key argumentative structure centers around explaining the discrepancy between the titles of the first and second editions of Descartes' Meditations. The main claims are:

1. Descartes changed the subtitle in the second edition (A1)
2. The first edition's subtitle was misleading since it promised a proof of immortality that wasn't actually in the text (A4, A5)
3. The wording of the first edition's title likely did not come from Descartes himself (A6)

The paper argues that the original subtitle was meant to say "immaterialitas" (immateriality) rather than "immortalitas" (immortality), and this error occurred during copying/printing against Descartes' intentions. This is supported by evidence from Baillet's biography (A8) and other writings by Descartes.

The argument structure shows how the author builds this case by first establishing the factual changes between editions, then demonstrating the mismatch between the first title and the actual content, and finally providing evidence that the misleading wording was not Descartes' doing.
